<p>Test any existing forms if you haven't already. That should give you a good idea which questions users expect first. For example, do they expect to give you personal details at the start or do they want to deal with the task first and give you personal details at the end?</p>
<p>Here are some tips to help you get it right.</p>
<ul>
  <li>It may help to start with easy questions and to save more difficult or sensitive questions for later.</li>
  <li>Design for the most common scenarios first. Decide which group of users you want to prioritise.</li>
  <li><a href="/service-manual/content/how-to-write-good-questions/4-treat-it-like-a-conversation">Treat it like a conversation</a>. Listen for natural pauses, for example, between topics.</li>
  <li>Start with questions that let users know if they’re not eligible for the service, so you don’t waste their time.</li>
  <li>You could group questions according to where users will get the answer. For example, group contact information together and account information together. See the section on <a href="/service-manual/content/write-good-questions/4-treat-it-like-a-conversation#consider-the-effort-involved-in-answering">considering the effort involved in answering</a>.</li>
  <li>If you have similar fields, put required ones ahead of optional ones.</li>
  <li>Do card sorting with users to understand which questions go together.</li>
</ul>

<p>Test the order when you <a href="/service-manual/content/how-to-write-good-questions/7-test-your-questions">test your questions</a>.</p>

